<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko: Accord To Be Signed by Majority </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko: Accord To Be Signed by Majority </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904130094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1117 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904130094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 19 TASS -- The agreement on civil peace 
and accord will be signed by the majority of political forces in 
the Kremlin on April 28, upper chamber speaker Vladimir Shumeyko 
said in an interview with journalists here on Tuesday. He 
claimed that "the influence of constructive forces in society 
now is greater than that of right- and left-wing radicals". 
  In the speaker's opinion, it will become clear at the 
agreement's signing ceremony who and why does not sign the 
document leading to civil accord. The division of political 
forces into groups will be clearly seen at that time. However, 
if somebody does not sign the agreement, this will not split the 
society, since the document will be open for signing after April 
28, he stressed. 
  Asked about the influence of political forces in Russia's 
life, Shumeyko noted that "centrist parties have a prospect to 
become influential". This will take place when society will 
"outgrow an yearn for rallies". The speaker believes that the 
influence of political parties on Russia is now "purely 
nominal". In contrast to Moscow, many in provinces do not know 
what political parties mean and what their role is. People 
judge about them by actions of their leaders. 
  Shumeyko claimed that the Russian president should not rely 
on a single party. He should be "above party movements and rely 
on the average derivative in order to find the only correct 
solution as head of state". 
  The speaker noted that "if we are to judge about parties by 
factions in the lower chamber, it will be clear that the 
situation when communists block democrats' decisions and vice 
versa, persists". This leads to the centre's consolidation, 
Shumeyko underlined. True, he said with regret, "the centre is 
being formed not in favour of reforms". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

