<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Proposes Yeltsin for President </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko Proposes Yeltsin for President </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904153794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1328 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904153794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chairman of the Federation Council Vladimir Shumeyko 
proposed advancing Boris Yeltsin's candidacy to the presidential 
elections in 1996. "Boris Yeltsin's stay in office for one more 
term would only benefit Russia," he told journalists in Moscow. 
Shumeyko believes that Yeltsin "has no right" to rely on any 
particular political forces, because none of them reflects the 
interests of broad sections of the population. 
  The political parties are mostly concentrated in the State 
Duma, he went on to say. "Their work shows that polarity in 
decision- making still persists: democrats are blocking the 
communists and vice versa," stated Shumeyko. He noted, that 
centrist tendencies were increasing. Among the centrist parties 
are the Party of Russian Unity and Concord, Women of Russia, the 
Communist and agrarian parties, and the New Regional Policy 
faction, said Shumeyko. However, the center favors conservative 
ideas rather than reforms, he went on to say. 
  He told Interfax that Russia should not hasten to join 
NATO's 
Partnership for Peace program. The main condition for doing so 
is joint work, equality and a clear-cut mechanism of 
implementing decisions, said Shumeyko. "The air strikes on the 
Serb positions by the US military command suggest that there is 
no such mechanism even in the UN Security Council," stated 
Shumeyko. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

