<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: Freedom of Expression Support Declines </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll: Freedom of Expression Support Declines </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1904121094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 19 Apr 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> MK1904121094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed INTERFAX report in the "In Brief" column] </F>
  [Text] Moscow -- The political and economic situation in 
Russia noticeably inhibits Russians' orientation toward the 
values of democracy and freedom of expression in society. Thus, 
in the past five years (from December 1988 to December 1993) the 
proportion of Russian citizens considering glasnost and freedom 
of expression important for themselves has declined from 51 to 
12 percent. This finding has been reported by the Institute for 
the Sociology of Parliamentarianism directed by Nugzar Betaneli. 
The poll conducted in March and April 1994 showed that even in 
Moscow, where democratic trends prevail, the level of 
socio-psychological intolerance has grown: The number of those 
who think that not everything in Russia (people, parties, 
movements, and mass media) should enjoy equal freedom of 
expression has grown from 28 percent (May 1993) to 43 percent 
(March 1994), while another 2 percent believe that everyone's 
freedom of expression must be limited. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

