<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Sends Chernomyrdin Letter on Bankruptcies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Sends Chernomyrdin Letter on Bankruptcies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904134994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1313 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 19 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin has addressed a letter to Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin stressing the need to resolve the problem of 
default payments and to enact bankruptcy procedures for 
loss-making enterprises, ITAR-TASS was told today by Aleksandr 
Livshits, head of a team of experts under the presidency. 
  Speaking about the need for bankruptcy procedures, Livshits 
stressed that if this measure was not adopted "the inflation is 
apt to reach 40-50 per cent at the first stage, by May 1944, and 
the next spiral of default payments will lead to the 
Ukrainisation of the Russian economy". 
  The expert believes that it is just as difficult to legalise 
bankruptcies as it was to liberalise prices in January 1992. 
But if that was the first step towards the Russian economy's 
switchover to market rails, today it is most necessary to make 
the second step. 
  Explaining the bankruptcy mechanism, Livshits, who is doctor 
of economic sciences, noted that a loss-making enterprise should 
be immediately privatised, turned into an open-type joint-stock 
society, and temporarily managed by a commission, made up of 
creditors and representatives of the State Property Committee. 
The commission will check the accounts of the bankrupt 
enterprise, will analyse its system of management, and will 
decide on the commodities it is to manufacture. Only then the 
enterprise will get the money it needs to restore its 
efficiency. "Moreover," Livshits stressed, "it will not be 
necessary to lay off the workers of an enterprise which 
voluntarily declares itself bankrupt or to lock up its gates. 
  The president's 4-page message to the prime minister 
envisages some long-term measures (circulation of bills and 
reform of banks), as well as some short-term steps. Thereby, 
Yeltsin assumes full responsibility for the second step of the 
reform, including the riddance of the Russian economy of 
inefficient enterprises. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

