<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Program for Developing Small, Medium Towns </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Program for Developing Small, Medium Towns </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904185294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1530 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspondent Natalya Cherepanova] </F>
  [Text] St. Petersburg April 19 TASS -- Russia is 
developing, in cooperation with the European Bank of 
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD), a federal programme on 
the development of small and medium towns. The Investment Bank 
of Reconstruction and Development of Small Russian Cities will 
be instituted for this purpose, Yevgeniy Malkov, the president 
of Russian Small Towns Union, told journalists on Tuesday at the 
presentation of the EBRD investment programmes in Russia. 
  The bulk of the investment projects are to be realized in 
St. 
Petersburg, Moscow and Nizhny Novgorod, but a considerable part 
of the Russian industries is situated in small towns. This is 
why Russia will come to a market economy only if it modernizes 
industry and transport in its small towns. 
  One of these programmes deals with reconstructing small 
ports 
on the Baltic, Black and Azov seas. Another one envisages 
reconstructing local airports and industrial facilities. 
  According to Uralvneshtorgbank official Sergey Obraz, "the 
Urals is a territory safe for investments because, no ethnic 
conflicts take place here, and local industry managed to 
preserve its high standards of research and development. 
Scientists and engineers working on defence enterprises (the 
Sverdlovsk region alone has five top-secret nuclear-technology 
towns) can produce new technologies, but cannot make money. 
This is why investment projects here should be launched before 
they give up their production capacities completely." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

