<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shortage of Draftees Expected </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shortage of Draftees Expected </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004082294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 0551 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004082294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] There will be a big shortage of draftees in the 
Russian army this spring. Only about 216,000 young men will be 
drafted, although the demand of the armed forces is 700,000. 
The draft and allocation to units will be completed by July 1, 
Commander of the Main Organizational and Mobilization Board of 
the Russian Armed Forces' General Headquarters General Vitaliy 
Bologov told INTERFAX on Tuesday. 
  He said that the shortage in the army is caused by the fact 
that many young men have the right to postpone their service, as 
well as by the worsening of draftees' health condition. The 
General noted that in the spring the armed forces can draft only 
27 percent of available "mobilization resources." He also said 
that in other countries the figure is 50 to 75 percent. 
  Bologov noted that the Defense Ministry will suggest that 
parliament introduce amendments in the near future to the laws 
on military service, on defense and some others in order to 
reduce the number of privileges and delays for draftees. 
  Commenting on the Russian president's decree on draft of 
citizens born in 1967-1976, Bologov noted that according to the 
Constitution of the country, a young man not older than 27 can 
be drafted to the army. 
  Bologov said that the autumn draft of 1993 was fulfilled to 
90.6 percent. He said that of more than 500,00 citizens 480,000 
were sent to serve in the army. The General added that 320,000 
draftees graduated from secondary professional-technical schools. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

