<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Alert Planned for Interior Troops 1 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No Alert Planned for Interior Troops 1 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904165694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1328 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904165694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On May 1, the Russian interior troops will be beefed 
up, but they will not be put in a state of alert, Interior 
Troops Commander Colonel General Anatoliy Kulikov announced 
during a briefing in Moscow. He said that the security of some 
of the military facilities would be enhanced to exclude the 
seizure of weapons and military equipment. "But there are no 
plans to draw forces to Moscow from other regions," he said. 
  To quote Kulikov, on May 1, interior troops will be in 
reserve and help the police if necessary. Kulikov referred to 
the law which says that the interior troops shall not be used 
for dispersing unsanctioned rallies or demonstrations, but shall 
be involved in dealing with mass disturbances. He also 
announced that in a number of regions, above all in the North 
Caucasus, the interior troops had to act in the backdrop of a 
complicated criminal situation. In 1993, interior troops came 
under fire 130 times in North Ossetia and Ingushetia. As a 
result, seven servicemen were killed and 133 were wounded. This 
year, interior troops were attacked more than 20 times. 
  He proposed that the Interior Minister be allowed to change 
the structure and dislocation of the interior troops depending 
on the criminal situation. He also noted that almost 17,000 
interior troop servicemen had no housing. "Spending on the 
interior troops meets only 60 percent of our needs," said 
Kulikov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

