<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Border Troop Commander: Status of Troops Rising </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Border Troop Commander: Status of Troops Rising </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904131194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1203 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Borovkov] </F>
  [Text] Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky April 19 TASS -- "The 
status of border troops is rising, and I believe that the very 
concept of this structure is changing," Andrey Nikolayev, 
commander-in-chief of Russian border troops, said in an 
interview with ITAR-TASS here on Tuesday. He said this, 
replying to the question of whether his appointment a member of 
the Russian Security Council means a higher status of border 
troops within the system of ensuring the state's security. 
  "While the border was earlier the only boundary designed to 
fight single infiltrators," Nikolayev continued, "now we face an 
all-out 'offensive' of smugglers, drug and arms dealers as well 
as mobs. We need new border troops, and we are now working on 
this issue." 
  Nikolayev who was recently appointed a member of the 
Security 
Council by the Russian president's decree, is now making an 
inspection tour of the Russian Far East. 
  "The Russian Far Eastern bounderies have some features 
distinguishing them from other parts of the state border," 
Nikolayev noted. Their main part runs across sea expanses, 
forcing us to keep here powerful coast guard forces. "The main 
problem here is that it is an area of constant violations of 
fishing regulations. "We should find a way to settle this 
problem not by force but legally," Nikolayev stressed. "This 
area is of interest not only to Russia but to other states as 
well which should understand that they upset the ecological and 
biological balance in this part of the world ocean by destroying 
rich marine resources." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

