<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kebich Rejects Accusations on Monetary Unification </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kebich Rejects Accusations on Monetary Unification </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904195894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1825 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904195894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belarusian Premier Vyacheslav Kebich reacted with 
irony to the statements by Belarusian ex-speaker Stanislav 
Shuskevich and leader of the Belarusian Popular Front Zenon 
Poznyak who called the signing of Russian-Belarusian documents 
on the unification of monetary systems "a crime," 
press-secretary of the Belarusian prime minister Vladimir 
Zametalin told INTERFAX. 
  He said that "Kebich considers such accusations another 
provocation by national-reformists, and the treaty with Russia, 
in the opinion of the prime minister, is the only way to 
preserve Belarus' sovereignty." 
  Zametalin also announced the prime minister's plans to hold 
an open meeting of the presidium of the Council of Ministers in 
the near future with unlimited participation of all interested 
parties and mass media in order to stop speculations around 
"so-called corruption." (He referred to accusations against 
some high-ranking officials made by chairman of the recently 
disbanded parliamentary commission against corruption Aleksandr 
Lukashenko) 
  Zametalin also said that the government meeting will be 
attended by top officials of the Republic's General Prosecutor's 
Office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

