<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Natural Gas Supplies to Industry To Be Cut </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Natural Gas Supplies to Industry To Be Cut </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904165594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1328 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904165594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moldova has decided to slash by one-third natural 
gas supplies to its industrial sector due to the country's huge 
debt for gas imports, said deputy prime Minister Valentin Cunev. 
  Moldova cannot repay the debt of 131 billion Russian rubles 
with money from its treasury, Cunev said in a television 
program. "The (state) budget is well-balanced and its deficit 
must not exceed 3.5 percent of the gross domestic product," 
which prompts a "very simple" solution -- "if you can't pay cut 
down your consumption," he said. 
  Moldova consumes no more energy today than four years ago 
but 
"produces much fewer goods," Cunev said. 
  He said it would be cheaper for Moldova to buy crude oil in 
the Middle East and have it refined in Romania. But Moldova 
does not have enough hard currency to pay for this, while 
oil-exporters in the Commonwealth of Independent States accept 
Moldovan goods as payment. 
  Russia has pledged to provide Moldova with 3.5 billion cubic 
meters of gas this year, while the Russian gas monopoly Gazprom 
a few days ago axed by one-third its supplies to Moldova due to 
the latter's arrears. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

