<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Says Bosnian Talks Must Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Says Bosnian Talks Must Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904155494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1457 
GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1904155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow, 19 Apr -- "There cannot be any question of 
terminating talks with one of the parties to a settlement of the 
conflict in Bosnia," Mikhail Demurin, deputy head of a 
directorate of the Russian Foreign Ministry's information and 
press department, told a briefing today. "The talks must 
continue. This is our general line and we will not retreat from 
this line," he stressed. 
  The Russian side believes that "the only way to resolve 
conflicts in former Yugoslavia and other parts of the world is 
to hold political talks." This position, the diplomat said, is 
the reason why Russia is calling for restraint, compromise, and 
mutual understanding. 
  The Foreign Ministry spokesman blamed the so-called "party 
of 
war" for inflaming the situation around Gorazde by "recklessly 
gambling on the achievement of military victory." According to 
him, this gambling will first of all inflict damage on the 
Serbian people themselves. 
  M. Demurin pointed to the inappropriateness of raising the 
question of lifting sanctions in a situation "where the Serbian 
troops are at Gorazde." In his opinion, the resolution of this 
question is being postponed for some time, depending on which 
way the situation develops." He said that during the recent 
talks between Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and 
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, the Russian side promised 
Belgrade its "most active support" in resolving the questions of 
lifting the sanctions stage-by-stage. He said: "During the same 
meeting, other agreements were also reached, in particular, 
unblocking the situation around Gorazde." The Serbian side gave 
appropriate assurances, M. Demurin stressed. "However, the 
words of those who gave these assurances are totally at odds 
with their deeds," the Russian diplomat said. 

</TEXT>

