<F P=103> AU2004092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Moscow, April 20 (AFP) -- President Boris 
Yeltsin chaired Wednesday a meeting of his top advisers in the 
Russian Security Council expected to focus on the Bosnian 
conflict. [passage omitted] 
  Meanwhile, the Russian newspaper SEGODNYA reported Wednesday 
that Moscow had decided to recall its ambassador to Belgrade 
Gennadiy Shikin for consultations, heralding a possible severing 
of relations with the rump Yugoslavia. 
  The paper, quoting a reliable source at the Russian Foreign 
Ministry, said that Moscow "no longer believes in the 
possibility of an adequate political dialogue with the Bosnian 
Serbs. 
  "The theories according to which (Bosnian Serb leader) 
Radovan Karadzic no longer controls his troops are false. It is 
obvious that there is a deliberate intention (on the part of the 
Serbs) to prevent any constructive dialogue between the warring 
sides," the paper said. 
  The Foreign Ministry would neither confirm nor deny the 
SEGODNYA report. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

