<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow's Influence on Serbs Seen as Limited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow's Influence on Serbs Seen as Limited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2004080094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 20 Apr 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK2004080094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Mikhail Karpov report in the "Crisis" column under general </F>
headline: "Stop Any Negotiations With the Bosnian Serbs. This 
Has Been Urged by Vitaliy Churkin, the Russian Federation 
President's Special Envoy"] 
  [Text] It seems that the latest negotiations by Kozyrev in 
Belgrade and Churkin in Pale were used by Milosevic and Karadzic 
in their purely egoistic interests. In this event it appears 
that U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who accused the 
Serbs of spinning a web of lies and deceptive statements about 
their intentions in Gorazde, is right. According to him, "the 
Serbs are lying to the United Nations and even to their 
traditional ally, Russia." 
  This probably accounts for the sharpness of Vitaliy 
Churkin's 
statement. Incidentally, the West missed no chance of noting 
that the Serbs' tactics in Gorazde annoy the Russian leadership. 
This led to the conclusion that Moscow may not after all have 
so many levers to influence them. And even that relations 
between it and Belgrade are not as friendly as was thought 
earlier. In this context it is supposed that President Yeltsin, 
whose statement on the Bosnian crisis was expected yesterday, 
will take all this into account and start cooperating with the 
West more closely. It is unlikely, however, that the 
presidential statement will coincide in tone with Churkin's 
pronouncements. 
  The latter, if facing far from easy explanations to the 
parliament, the unmistakably pro-Serbian mood of the majority of 
whose deputies is well known. Apparently Churkin will also have 
a dialogue with the military who up until now have had certain 
disagreements with the Foreign Ministry's position on a number 
of issues. It would be premature in these conditions to talk 
about a radical change of line in Russia's policy in the 
Balkans. It is clear, however, that it can be essentially 
adjusted, which does not bode any comfort to the "cheats" from 
the Serb leadership both in Pale and Belgrade. But in any 
event, it is hard to expect that on the question of a Balkan 
settlement Russia will resort to the children's formula, "the 
cat has left her kittens...." ["koshka brosila kotyat"] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-16816 </DOCNO>
