<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Commitees, U.S. Senators To Discuss Start II </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Commitees, U.S. Senators To Discuss Start II </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004083394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 0551 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004083394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Preparations for the ratification of the START-2 
treaty signed on January 3 will be the focus of a meeting 
between a number of committees of the Russian State Duma and two 
U.S. senators, Sam Nunn and Richard Lugar, coming to Moscow in 
mid-May, the defense committee chairperson, Sergey Yushenkov, 
told a State Duma session Tuesday. 
  The session was told that the ratification of START-2 should 
follow the enacting of its predecessor, START-1, signed on July 
31 1991. 
  Despite the fact that the treaty has already been ratified 
by 
Russia, Ukraine, Belarus and Kazakhstan since the break-up of 
the Soviet Union, it will come into force only after the 
exchange of ratification letters with the USA. The session was 
told that the process is hindered by Ukraine where "political 
struggle for this or that status as a nuclear state is going 
on," according to the head of the disarmament department of the 
Russian Foreign Ministry, Oleg Sokolov. 
  As many as 3,800-4,250 nuclear ammo will be destroyed during 
the first stage of the START-2 treaty's implementation, which 
will last for seven years -- the same as the START-1 treaty. 
Another 3,000- 3,500 items of nuclear ammunition will be 
destroyed during the second stage which will last until 2003. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

