<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Organization Makes Recommendation on Loans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Organization Makes Recommendation on Loans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904165094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1328 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The U.S. Chamber of Trade and Commerce [USCTC] in 
Russia, uniting about 180 companies has recommended its members 
to refrain from lending credit to juridical persons in Russia, 
head of the USCTC Investment Committee George Reese said 
speaking in Moscow on Tuesday. 
  He said that a number of Russian government officials were 
informed about the move following the misinterpretation of 
President Yeltsin's decree of last December by some members of 
the Russian taxation bodies. They appear to interpret the 
decree as a cancellation of a provision of the law on the value 
added tax whereby credits are exempt from VAT. This enables tax 
collectors to levy a 23 percent tax on foreign credits to 
Russian juridical persons which is unacceptable to their foreign 
partners, Reese said. 
  U.S. company officials taking part in a news conference 
described the situation as extreme and demanded immediate 
clarifications from the Russian government. Until then, we will 
refrain from any investment here, member of the USCTC Board of 
Directors Larry Anderson said. 
  For his part, Reese said that granting loans in conditions 
of 
such commercial uncertainty were fraught with dire implications 
for U.S. companies. A refusal to provide credits will restrict 
the flow of much-sought investment in the Russian economy, he 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

