<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on PLO Chairman 'Arafat's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on PLO Chairman 'Arafat's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kozyrev, 'Arafat Hold News Conference </H4>

<F P=102> LD1904152194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1236 
GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1904152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Sergey Babkin and </F>
Yuriy Tyssovskiy] 
  [Excerpts] Moscow, 19 Apr -- Russian Foreign Affairs 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev today paid tribute to Yasir 'Arafat, 
president of the state of Palestine and chairman of the PLO 
Executive Committee, for the responsibility and courage he has 
shown to establish peace in the Near East. At a news 
conference, he summed up the results of the talks which have 
taken place with the Palestinian side at the Foreign Ministry's 
residence. These talks covered a wide range of issues connected 
with a Near East settlement and bilateral relations. 
  The head of the Russian Foreign Ministry said that at the 
talks in Moscow the sides continued the Palestinian-Russian 
dialogue which has been going on for several years now and which 
was given powerful impetus as a result of President Boris 
Yeltsin's initiative. This initiative was discussed by the 
sides in Tunis, where a "bold and fundamental" political 
decision was made to return to the negotiating table in spite of 
existing difficulties. "Today we discussed those difficulties, 
we know about them, and we are determined to eliminate all 
obstacles to a comprehensive settlement," the minister stressed. 
He assured Y. 'Arafat of Russian support for the PLO's policy 
of opposing extremists, and noted that the heads of state of 
Palestine and Russia are in constant contact through the Russian 
president's special envoy Viktor Posuvalyuk via a regular 
exchange of messages. 
  Y. 'Arafat described his visit to Moscow as especially 
important given the difficult circumstances under which it is 
taking place. He said: "A double historical, political, and 
moral responsibility for the situation in the region rests on 
Mr. Kozyrev, since it was he and U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher who countersigned the Palestinian-Israeli 
agreement." Y. 'Arafat said that today he discussed with the 
head of the Russian Foreign Ministry ways of overcoming those 
obstacles which are preventing the implementation of the 
Palestinian-Israeli "Gaza-Jericho, First" agreement, and namely 
those "delays and maneuvers" to which the Israeli side is 
resorting. "I reminded the minister that the deadline under the 
agreement for the withdrawal of Israeli troops from the 
territories coming under Palestinian autonomy expired on 13 
April. In spite of this, nothing has changed on the ground," 
the PLO leader said. 
  "All of this will lead to time being lost and will allow 
those forces which oppose the agreement to close ranks and 
mobilize their actions against the establishment of peace in the 
region." He warned that the only alternative to peace is 
anarchy and "Balkanization" of the region. [passage omitted] 
  After the talks, the sides signed a Russo-Palestinian 
agreement on the prospects for bilateral cooperation in 
politics, economics, and culture. 
  Earlier today, the Palestinian head of the state laid a 
wreath at the tomb of the unknown soldier, and held talks with 
Russian State Duma Chairman Ivan Rybkin and Russian Interior 
Minister Viktor Yerin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-16825 </DOCNO>
