<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EBRD Holds Annual Meeting in St Petersburg </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EBRD Holds Annual Meeting in St Petersburg </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Gerashchenko Calls For More Credits </H4>

<F P=102> LD1904215394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1825 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904215394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The chairman of the Central Bank of Russia (CBR), 
Viktor Gerashchenko, has called on the European Bank for 
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) to boost credits to purely 
Russian enterprises rather than joint ventures with 
participation of western companies. Speaking at the closing 
ceremony of an annual meeting of the EBRD board in St. 
Petersburg Tuesday, Gerashchenko pointed out that quite a number 
of reliable companies capable of maintaining civilized relations 
with the bank had appeared in Russia. He highly praised the 
EBRD's efforts in assisting Russia's small businesses and 
supposed that its dialog with Russian business would be even 
more productive, if carried out through the CBR. 
  Commenting on the EBRD's activities last year, Gerashchenko 
noted that the amount of credits actually used for Russian 
projects had increased by more than 10 times and reached $120 Mn 
[million]. In his opinion, the EBRD board of directors might 
function as the coordinator of various states' efforts for the 
support of Russian reforms. 
  EBRD President Jacques de Larosiere pointed out that this 
body would use a more flexible approach to its relations with 
East and Central European countries and pay more attention to 
their small and medium-sized businesses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

