<H3> <TI>   Japan `Positively Views' Moscow Initiative on Korea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan `Positively Views' Moscow Initiative on Korea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904192194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1128 
GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1904192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vladimir Solntsev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 19 Apr -- Japan positively views the recent 
Moscow initiative on convening an international conference on 
the questions of security in the Korean peninsula and its 
nonnuclear status, according to the formula "six plus two" and 
thinks it reflects Russia's serious interests in solving the 
North Korean nuclear problem, stated Japanese Ambassador Koji 
Watanabe in his exclusive interview with the ITAR-TASS 
correspondent. 
  Having pointed out the similarity of positions taken by 
Tokyo 
and Moscow, the diplomat stressed Japan's intention to continue 
to exchange views on this problems in close contact with Moscow. 
The ambassador said that questions of easing the situation in 
the Korean Peninsula, including the problem of Korean 
unification, are constantly on the agenda in the 
Japanese-Russian political dialogue. 
  Watanabe expressed the view that the most important thing at 
present will be to make sure that the DPRK allows the IAEA 
[International Atomic Energy Agency] inspectors to examine its 
most suspect nuclear installations in accordance with the recent 
appeal made by the UN Security Council chairman. The diplomat 
also pointed at Japan's intention to "resolutely demand" that 
North Korea continues to remain within the framework of the 
nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty and adhere to the North-South 
joint declaration on the nonnuclear status of the Korean 
peninsula. 

</TEXT>

