<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Meets on Venue for Next Round of Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Meets on Venue for Next Round of Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904105294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0924 
GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1904105294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vladimir </F>
Gavrilov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 19 Apr -- The Tajik opposition delegation is 
holding a conference in Moscow today to draw up its proposal on 
the venue and date for the next round of talks with 
representatives of official Dushanbe. It is expected to be held 
either in Islamabad or in Tehran. According to the Tajik 
Embassy in Moscow, the opposition does not insist on Emomali 
Rakhmonov, chairman of the republic's Supreme Soviet, being 
there. 
  The ITAR-TASS correspondent learned from the same sources 
that by and large the Dushanbe delegation positively assesses 
the results of the first round, at which agreement was reached 
with the opposition not to allow hostile actions on the 
Afghan-Tajik border. 
  The sides have expressed their determination to continue 
dialogues and to seek a compromise, even though their stands on 
the agenda remain unchanged. Thus, the Dushanbe delegation 
still believes it is advisable first to ensure peace on the 
Afghan-Tajik border and the return of refugees, and then to hold 
a referendum on the Tajik constitution and presidential 
elections. On the other hand, the opposition will come to the 
next round with the same package of documents as before 
concerning the refugee problem, political settlement in the 
country, the revocation of the ban on the activities of 
political parties and movements, setting up a State Council made 
up of independent persons, and a referendum on the constitution. 
  The first round of talks between the Tajik authorities and 
the opposition has been taking place in Moscow since 6 April. 
On 17 April Hoji Akbar Turajonzoda, one of the eminent 
opposition leaders, arrived from Islamabad to take part. Also 
present has been Muhammadsharif Himmatzoda, chairman of the 
Islamic Rebirth Party. The talks have been conducted with the 
assistance of Ramiro Piriz Ballon, the UN secretary general's 
special envoy in Tajikistan. 

</TEXT>

