<H3> <TI>   Meets With Iliescu, Melescanu </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meets With Iliescu, Melescanu </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004084394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1755 
GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004084394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Nikolay Morozov] </F>
  [Text] Bucharest, 19 Apr -- "It is vital for Armenia and 
Romania to establish good relations," emphasized Vahan Papazyan, 
foreign minister of the Republic of Armenia, who is in Bucharest 
to discuss the opportunities for developing bilateral 
Armenian-Romanian ties and economic cooperation in particular. 
  In the course of their talks, Armenia's and Romania's 
foreign 
ministers stressed the need for a speedy completion of the work 
on a political treaty between the two countries. Papazyan 
informed his counterpart on the situation in the Transcaucasus 
and the latest steps aimed at settling tensions in 
Nagorno-Karabakh. [Romanian Foreign Minister] Teodor Melescanu 
presented the main directions of Romania's foreign policy, 
described the current stage of its relations with NATO and the 
EC, as well as with neighboring countries. Agreement was 
reached at the talks to extend cooperation within the framework 
of international organizations, namely the CSCE and the UN, and 
to extend cooperation in the Black Sea area. 
  The need to further relations was also emphasized at the 19 
April reception for Armenia's foreign minister by Romanian 
President Ion Iliescu. The two sides discussed conflicts in 
Nagorno-Karabakh and in Bosnia-Herzegovina, to the settlement of 
which both Armenia and Romania are committed. "We tried to find 
common viewpoints on these problems," noted Papazyan, who passed 
to the Romanian president a message from the president of 
Armenia and an invitation to visit the country. 
  On 18 April, the Armenian ambassador to Romania presented 
his 
credentials to the Romanian head of state. The official opening 
of the Armenian Embassy in Bucharest is to take place in the 
next few days. 

</TEXT>

