<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Attacks Aimed To Force Signing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Attacks Aimed To Force Signing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1904150594 Baku TURAN in English 2308 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1904150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Baku TURAN </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Baku, April 18, TURAN--Since the beginning of the 
Moscow summit of the CIS leaders on 15 April, Armenian armed 
forces have launched a large-scale attack in the direction of 
the northern and north-eastern sections of Azerbaijan with the 
intent of occupying the main sections of the Geranboyskiy 
[Shaumyanovskiy] and Terterskiy regions of Azerbaijan. This 
attack was directed towards Ganja, Azerbaijan's second largest 
city as well as towards the southern section of the front with 
the seizure of the city of Beylagan. TURAN was informed by a 
government official who requested anonymity. 
  The Azeri leadership thinks that this military plan is aimed 
at destabilizing the situation in Azerbaijan, thereby compelling 
Baku to agree to the Russian proposal concerning the 
Armenian-Azeri conflict. It is widely known that the main terms 
of the proposal is the stationing of the Russian army in the 
conflict zone. 
  During the Moscow Summit government officials of Armenia 
told 
Azeri President Aliev that "the Russian army's deployment in the 
region of conflict will guarantee a ceasefire." 
  This statement made by the Armenian officials coincides with 
the statement made by Kazimirov, the representative of the 
Russian president for the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict which is 
pushing for a Russian peacemaking force role in the region. 
  It is widely known that Baku insists that the separation 
forces should consist of international units and act on the 
basis of United Nations and the CSCE mandate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

