<DATE1>  19 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister on Kiev-Moscow Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister on Kiev-Moscow Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904220094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1946 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904220094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Leonid Kotov, Vladimir </F>
Shvedov] 
  [Text] New Delhi 19 April TASS -- "Kiev pays major 
attention to the development of good-neighbourly and friendly 
relations with Russia and the Russian people," Ukrainian Foreign 
Minister Anatoliy Zlenko told a news conference here today. The 
Ukrainian minister is currently on an official visit to India. 
  "The major aim of our policy is consolidation of 
Ukrainian-Russian relations. The immediate elaboration of a 
comprehensive bilateral treaty on friendship and cooperation as 
it was agreed by the Commonwealth state and government heads 
will help this consolidation," he said. 
  "Work on the document has been done since 1993. 
Unfortunately, there was a delay in finalization of the 
agreement on reasons not depending on Ukraine. Meanwhile, 
Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and me were instructed 
by our presidents to boost the document's elaboration. The 
treaty is expected to reflect new realities in the 
Ukrainian-Russian relations and outline a way for the solution 
of the current problems. Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk 
invited Boris Yeltsin to come to Kiev on an official visit to 
sign the document," said the foreign minister. 
  "Permanent negotiations with Russia enable solution of any 
problems in bilateral relations. We are satisfied with 
Yeltsin's readiness to help remove obstacles on the way of 
development of our friendship and cooperation and his statement 
saying Russia respects territorial integrity of Ukraine, 
inviolability of its borders and sovereignty. 
  ``As for the division of the Black Sea Fleet, Kiev and 
Moscow 
are progressing step by step to the solution of this problem. A 
new agreement on the Black Sea Fleet that is being elaborated 
will focus on separate bases of the Russian and Ukrainian 
navies,'' said Zlenko. However, this, in his opinion, will not 
help to eliminate all problems related to the Black Sea Fleet's 
future. Experts are still to analyze the division parameters. 
  Ukraine is ready to have 15-20 per cent of the ships it 
received under the Moscow agreement signed in September 1993, 
said the foreign minister. The rest of the fleet will be passed 
over to Russia. The new document will give a fresh impetus to 
the work on remaining problems of the Black Sea Fleet, said 
Zlenko. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

