<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kyrgyz Army Reportedly Ousting Russian Officers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kyrgyz Army Reportedly Ousting Russian Officers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904115494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1013 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Maynayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek 19 April, TASS -- Russian officers 
complained that they are being ousted from the Kyrgyz Army on 
the pretext of anti-corruption drive and demanded that Kyrgyz 
President Askar Akayev restore order in the Army. 
  Russian officers of the Oshsk garrison located in the south 
of Kyrgyzstan said in an open letter addressed to President 
Akayev that recently, departments of the military prosecutor's 
office have begun to ouster Russian-speaking commanders from the 
Army "contrary to the will of Kyrgyz Defence Minister Myrzakan 
Subanov." 
  "In our opinion, military judicial bodies who have been 
looking for thieves stealing military and state property among 
Russian officers believe that if we have not gone home yet we 
have some sources of income encouraging us to stay. This is 
nonsense. We remain here because we swore allegiance here," 
says the letter signed by over 100 Russian officers, which was 
published by the "KYRGYZSTAN'S WORD" newspaper today. Russian 
commanders put the blame for the situation in the Army on Chief 
Military Prosecutor Kubat Kozhonaliyev. 
  Officers demanded that the president and commander in chief 
of the Kyrgyz Army Askar Akayev give guarantees that Russian 
officers will be able to perform their duties under normal 
conditions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

