<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechen Opposition Discusses Options for Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechen Opposition Discusses Options for Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904124694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1103 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904124694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Leaders of political movements opposed to President 
Johar Dudayev in Chechnya discussed how they might become 
involved in dialogue with Russia in Moscow on Monday [18 April]. 
  Interfax was informed by the opposition head quarters that 
the movements concerned discussed how they might form one body 
to represent both political parties and public and national 
movements in Chechnya opposed to Dudayev's policies. The 
stabilization of the situation inside the republic was also 
discussed. 
  One option for dialogue with Russia was that proposed by 
Russian Minister for Nationalities and Regional Policy Sergey 
Shakhray. That involved a presidential instruction stating, 
among other things, that the Russian government had been charged 
with "holding consultations with representatives of state power 
and of all political movements in the Chechen Republic" to find 
a way out of the social and political tension which had arisen. 
  Asked by Interfax why the meeting had taken place in Moscow, 
one opposition representative replied: "Not all opposition 
leaders are able to travel to Chechnya because they are being 
literally hunted down there." 

</TEXT>

