<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Groznyy Not Hopeful on Early Russian-Chechen Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Groznyy Not Hopeful on Early Russian-Chechen Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904202894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1825 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A top-ranking official of the Chechen presidential 
staff has said he doubted that a republican delegation would 
soon arrive in Moscow for bilateral consultations. In an 
interview with Interfax, he recalled that the Chechen government 
had taken a resolution under which all contacts with Russia were 
to be maintained solely through the Chechen Foreign Ministry. 
This decision was made last week in order to regulate Groznyy's 
relations with Moscow. 
  The chief of the staff of the Russian president, Sergey 
Filatov, told Interfax that consultations with Groznyy were 
supposed to involve both the republican authorities as well as 
political parties and movements of the Chechen republic. 
However, after a recent meeting of Russian and Chechen 
representatives the Chechen side said further talks would be 
inexpedient, for there were "no political forces in control of 
the political situation" in Russia. In addition, the Chechen 
leadership had been making statements that the opposition's 
participation in the talks in any form would be unrealistic. 
  In the meantime, Interfax learned from reliable sources that 
Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev consulted experts Monday on 
the possible imposition of a moratorium on talks with Russia. 
Interfax was told that the experts insisted on the moratorium 
in view of Russia's unconstructive position. 
  The same sources said Dudayev had not yet made his choice. 

</TEXT>

