<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   CIS Countries in Debt to Russia for Communications </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CIS Countries in Debt to Russia for Communications </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104104394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1030 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104104394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Galkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 21 TASS -- CIS countries owe to Russia 
altogether hundreds of billions of roubles for telephone and 
postal services, Vladimir Bulgak, Russian minister of 
communications, told ITAR-TASS. Meanwhile, Russia has fully 
repaid these republics for similar services. 
  The reason for one-way traffic in the settlement of accounts 
is that banks fail to settle the problem of so-called non-trade 
operations. Roubles freely flow to CIS states toward the 
payment for communications services, while the national 
currencies of CIS countries do not cross the Russian border 
without being exchanged for roubles at the appropriate rate. 
  In December last, communications ministers of CIS countries 
met in Minsk and issued a joint statement urging heads of CIS 
countries to influence their central banks to speed up mutual 
settlement, Bulgak said. Certain progress is in the offing, but 
the problem has not been solved in a cardinal way and the 
banking mechanism has not been adjusted. Money from Uzbekistan, 
Ukraine and other countries, even if they have it, cannot reach 
Russia. 
  "I talked on the matter with Chairman of the Russian Central 
Bank Viktor Gerashchenko four times. There is voluminous 
correspondence with the bank on the matter", Bulgak said. "We 
tried to cope with the situation by mutual settlement, clearing, 
barter and other settlement, but all this does not amount to a 
civilised way of dealing with the problem", Bulgak said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-16938 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov077cc_94005" </HT>


