<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Concerned by Lower Russian Gas Supplies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Concerned by Lower Russian Gas Supplies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004172594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1347 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004172594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cutbacks in Russian gas exports to Moldova will hit 
living standards, Vice Premier Valeriu Bulgaru who is 
responsible for the agro-industrial complex believes. In an 
interview with INTERFAX on Wednesday, he said the government was 
seeking to raise extra funds to be able to clear arrears for gas 
imports from Russia. 
  Bulgar said the cabinet was working hard to try to resolve 
the problem of a trade deficit with Russia. 
  At the same time, he said the problem of gas imports from 
Russia was of general concern from government officials down to 
ordinary consumers. In his view, the mechanisms of a market 
economy will push energy consumers towards unusual 
decisionmaking. 
  On Tuesday, one other Vice Premier Valentin Cunev whose area 
of responsibility covers transport, construction and energy said 
that gas supply to industrial consumers would be reduced by a 
third. He called on consumers to stick to the principle of 
"reduce consumption if you cannot pay." 

</TEXT>

