<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zlenko Cited on Failed Oil Talks With Iran </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zlenko Cited on Failed Oil Talks With Iran </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2004095094 Moscow KOMMERSANT-DAILY in Russian 20 Apr 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> MK2004095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMMERSANT-DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Natalya Kalashnikova: "Ukraine-Iran Talks. All </F>
Oil Roads Lead to Moscow"] 
  [Text] The results of a mission to Tehran by Ukraine 
Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko that ended yesterday have 
disappointed both sides. The contracts on deliveries of Iranian 
oil to Kiev are recognized as dead and buried. Ukraine could 
not after all get "black gold" either by the oil pipeline 
running across Azerbaijan or by tankers across the Black Sea 
because the Turkish side would not let them pass through the 
Bosporus. 
  Oil contacts with Tehran that saw the light of day as a 
result of Kiev's seeking economic independence from Moscow 
called for the supply of 5 million tonnes of "black gold" as 
early as 1992, and another 4 million in 1993. There were plans 
under which the "Iranian oil for Ukrainian metal" barter scheme 
was supposed to have reached the $7 billion level. There was 
also talk of a really pipe-dream project, of a direct oil and 
gas pipeline from Iran to Ukraine. But it was perhaps not 
fated. Mr. Zlenko has characterized the situation with failed 
deliveries as a stalemate. 
  Now there is a new deal in the offing. Iran intends to buy 
from Kiev military hardware manufactured in Ukraine, in 
particular Antonov-type military transport planes and spares for 
them. Since there are no diplomatic constraints for such 
bilateral relations, this understanding appears rather realistic. 
  A bilateral commission to coordinate economic cooperation 
was 
formed. As for political ties, Tehran has so far offered to 
Kiev mediation in freeing Ukrainian POW's in Afghanistan (there 
are nearly 80 of them). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

