<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tarasyuk Says Russian Article `Provocative Lie' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tarasyuk Says Russian Article `Provocative Lie' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004185294 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1600 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At the request of journalists, Deputy Ukrainian 
Foreign Minister Borys Tarasyuk commented on the article: 
Probable Plans of Improbable Enemy, published in KOMSOMOLSKAYA 
PRAVDA on 19 April. The article deals with the allegedly worked 
out plans of landing Ukrainian troops in Kuban and the Don 
[river]. Other so-called instances of the production of various 
kinds of weapons here [in Ukraine] are provided in the article. 
  Tarasyuk referred to this article as an outright provocative 
lie by the Moscow-based newspaper. According to him, this 
refers, in particular, to information about the production of 
tactical missiles at PivdenMash [southern machine-building plant 
in Dnepropetrovsk] and work on manufacturing binary, chemical, 
and bacteriological weapons allegedly under way here in Ukraine. 
  The deputy foreign minister reminded in this connection that 
our state is a signatory of the convention banning the above 
weapons and it strictly abides by its provisions. In Tarasyuk's 
opinion, such publications prove that KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA 
probably takes an active part in fanning up anti-Ukrainian 
sentiments in Russian society and tries to undermine the process 
of normalizing relations between the two neighboring states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

