<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks `Completely Satisfactory' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks `Completely Satisfactory' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004220294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1347 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004220294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] "The outcome of the inter-Tajik talks held in 
Moscow can be qualified as "completely satisfactory." The main 
thing is that a dialogue began, and that it proceeded 
constructively enough. It's also indicative that the launch of 
the negotiating mechanism led to lowering the intensity of 
violations on the border between Tajikistan and Afghanistan," 
the Director of the 3d Asian Department of Russia's Foreign 
Ministry, Yuriy Kotov, told INTERFAX on Wednesday. 
  According to him, "nothing great" was expected from the 
talks 
in Moscow. "We did not expect the two sides to reach 
comprehensive agreements at once. It's gratifying enough that 
they worked out an extensive agenda, adopted a statement on the 
need to refrain from any actions conducive to complicating the 
process of talks, agreed to form a commission on refugees, and 
coordinated a joint communique," the diplomat said. 

</TEXT>

