<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Sources' Say Opposition Planning New Provocations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Sources' Say Opposition Planning New Provocations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004164894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1410 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridnyova] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe 20 April TASS -- The Tajik opposition is 
preparing new provocations on the Tajik-Afghan border to 
destabilise the situation in the region and foil the second 
round of inter-Tajik talks due to take place either in Tehran or 
Islamabad, competent sources in Dushanbe told ITAR-TASS. 
  The sources said that Tajik opposition forces based in the 
Afghan provinces of Kunduz and Takhar are planning a series of 
attacks on Russian border outposts and Tajik border villages. 
There is also information indicating their intention to mine 
one of the sections of the Tajik-Afghan border patrolled by the 
Pyanj border troop unit. Mobile terrorist groups have been 
concentrated near the Imam Sahib Province, and weapons and 
military machinery are being brought in. 
  The sources claimed they had proof that the go-ahead to 
proceed with acts of terrorism was given by the government in 
exile led by Tajik national Sa'id Abdullo Nuri. The acts will 
be carried out by field commanders from the so-called 
Kumsangir-Pyanj resistance front. 
  The sources said all these activities are taking place in 
the 
districts controlled by the Afghan military whose leaders have 
repeatedly confirmed their readiness to help stabilise the 
situation on the Tajik-Afghan border and prevent provocations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

