<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Spokesman on Signing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Spokesman on Signing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104112294 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1000 GMT 
21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2104112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Remarks by Vyacheslav Kostikov, press secretary for </F>
President Boris Yeltsin, "this morning" in Moscow -- recorded] 
  [Text] Yesterday in the evening one of the last versions, 
if not the very last, of the text was drawn up to be submitted 
to the State Duma. Today this document will be handed over to 
the president and to the State Duma, where it will be discussed. 
I would like to inform you that this document will now be 
called A Treaty on Public Accord [Dogovor ob Obshchestvennom 
Soglasii]. This is a truly agreed upon text. It takes into 
account comments made by factions, parties, and public 
organizations, including the comments of Communists and the 
Liberal Democratic Party. The text has become more specific 
and, if you like, milder in its political part. During the 
process of consultations several provisions, which can be used 
for confrontation purposes, were removed from it. In particular, 
paragraphs on sanctions against those who violate the conditions 
of the accords were removed. 
  As you know, a week is left before signing. Today I spoke to 
Boris Nikolayevich on this topic and asked him how much he hopes 
for success. He said that he is optimistic. He hopes for 
success and believes in it. The president understands that not 
everyone will sign this document, but the main political forces 
and groups will sign it. In our view, the necessary mass of 
political will toward an accord will be created -- not just 
created, but registered as well. 

</TEXT>

