<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin on Opposition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin on Opposition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004164694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1422 
GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 20 Apr -- "The political situation in Russia 
has begun to stabilize," Russian President Boris Yeltsin stated, 
opening a meeting with heads of administrations of Russia's 
krays and oblasts today. 
  Boris Yeltsin said that there has been real collaboration 
with the Federation Council and the State Duma. "I have 
frequent meetings with Vladimir Shumeyko and Ivan Rybkin, we 
discuss issues of concern to Russia, and we reach agreement in a 
calm atmosphere. This style of work has a positive effect on the 
general political improvement in the country," the president 
said. 
  Boris Yeltsin confirmed that the signing of the Agreement on 
Civic Peace and Accord will take place on 28 April in St. 
George's Hall of the Grand Kremlin Palace. About 140 
organizations are expected to take part in the ceremony. The 
president called for the agreement to be signed by all branches 
of power, political parties, and public organizations. He 
believes that representatives of the power structures of the 
krays, oblasts, and Russian Federation republics should also 
sign the document. 
  Of those political forces who have so far opposed signing 
the 
agreement, Boris Yeltsin said: "We will not insist on them 
signing this document." Russians, he added "will see for 
themselves what the words of such leaders and their programs 
mean in practice." The head of state noted that, so far, only 
the Communists have stated their opposition to signing the 
agreement, but "perhaps, this only applies to a section of their 
leadership," the president remarked. 
  "We want this document to be a major political step, like in 
Spain, where a similar memorandum was also signed," he said. A 
special coordinating commission should monitor implementation of 
the agreement, the president believes. 
  I think, said Boris Yeltsin, that the accords on military 
issues initialled in March 1994 create a legal and diplomatic 
framework for completing the withdrawal of Russian troops from 
the territory of Latvia, and for resolving questions relating to 
this matter in a civilized manner. "They became possible as a 
result of sensible compromises and responsible attitudes, and 
they correspond to the real long-term interests not only of the 
peoples of our countries but of the entire region, of Europe as 
a whole." I hope "to have a meeting with Guntis Ulmanis in the 
near future where a package of the initialled agreements will be 
signed, which will become a turning-point in the relations 
between our two countries," Russian president said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

