<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties Criticize Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parties Criticize Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004125594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1201 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004125594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 20 TASS -- Having on the whole 
supported the draft civic concord agreement, the Democratic 
Russia Movement and the Socialist Workers Party have at the same 
time addressed to the presidential administration several 
complaints against this document, expected to be signed on April 
28. 
  In its statement, the Democratic Russia Movement calls for 
the deletion from the draft agreement of the thesis banning the 
use of assessments of the events of August 1991 and of 
September-October 1993 "as a pretext for deepening the 
confrontation". The movement's coordination council regards 
this thesis as "unacceptable". This view is shared by Valeriya 
Novodvorskaya, leader of the Russian Democratic Union. 
Interviewed by ITAR-TASS, the eminent human rights defender 
said: "How will the democrats be able to look into the eyes of 
the people, whom they had urged to man the barricades, if such a 
dubious ban is adopted?". 
  The supporters of Democratic Russia want some declarative 
commitments to be deleted from the text of the agreement and a 
clearer delimitation of responsibilities for the fulfilment of 
the memorandum terms. 
  Chairman of the Socialist Workers Party Lyudmila Vartazarova 
moves to delete from the draft agreement paragraphs duplicating 
the Russian Constitution or contradicting it in the part 
relating to the observance of human rights. Moreover, 
Vartazarova warns against "the discreditation of the very idea 
of national concord by rash and unconsidered actions". She 
suggests a procedure for the document's broad public discussion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

