<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Democratic Russia Demands Amendments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Democratic Russia Demands Amendments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004203794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1819 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004203794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The point stipulating that "the sides shall call for 
avoiding assessments of the events which occurred in August 1991 
and October 1993 as a pretext for deepening confrontation" must 
be left out of the agreement on civic accord in Russia because 
it is unacceptable, according to a statement of the coordinating 
council of Democratic Russia published in Moscow Wednesday. 
  The council supported Boris Yeltsin's initiative to develop 
an agreement between the major political forces and his declared 
course towards social consensus. At the same time, Democratic 
Russia listed a number of conditions which, in its opinion, must 
be met while developing and signing the agreement. 
  According to Democratic Russia, the Russian government can 
be 
allowed to sign the agreement only if it fulfills all its 
promises to pay salaries to state workers such as servicemen, 
medical and culture workers and policemen. Democratic Russia 
believes that persons and political forces whose actions 
violated Russian laws, who triggered and deliberately organized 
mass disorders, fanned ethnic differences and called for war and 
violence must not be allowed to sign the agreement. 
  The agreement must impose a responsibility before society 
upon everyone who signs it, Democratic Russia maintained. The 
movement's political council believes that the agreement should 
clearly outline the obligations of all sides, including the 
president, the government, the Federal Assembly, political 
parties, trade unions and other social organizations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

