<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communists Undecided </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Communists Undecided </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004172194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1437 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 20 TASS -- Russian Communists are still 
hesitating about signing Boris Yeltsin's memorandum on Civil 
Peace and Accord. The ceremony is scheduled for April 28. 
Gennadiy Zyuganov, the leader of the Russian Communist Party 
representing the moderate branch of the movement, said on 
Wednesday that the final decision on whether to sign the 
memorandum will be taken at a party national conference on April 
23-24. 
  However, speaking at a news conference today, Zyuganov 
expressed doubts that any true accord could be reached if 
signing to a document is limited by one fixed day. "If we take 
(civil) truce and accord seriously, I stand for a gradual 
approach towards such a variant which, instead of ideology, 
would rather focus on the national and state interests and take 
into account Russia's traditions, contain a mechanism of 
stabilizing the situation", the communist leader said. Zyuganov 
reiterated his support of the idea that "a government of 
national confidence should come to power by democratic means" in 
Russia. 

</TEXT>

