<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Salvation Front Official Comments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Salvation Front Official Comments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004165094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1330 
GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 20 Apr -- The National Salvation Front (NSF) 
intends to hold a session of the NSF Council this Sunday [24 
April]. It is to elect the NSF leadership and discuss the 
organization's immediate tasks. The ITAR-TASS correspondent 
learned this today from Ilya Konstantinov, chairman of the NSF 
Executive Committee. 
  The activities of the organization were suspended following 
the events of 3-4 October 1993, while Konstantinov himself was 
arrested. He was released from jail following the amnesty 
resolution passed by the State Duma. 
  Asked by the ITAR-TASS correspondent to give his assessment 
of the Accord for Russia movement, which is being set up with 
the help of Aleksandr Rutskoy, Konstantinov said it was too 
early to do this. At this stage the NSF is distancing itself 
from the movement. 
  Gennadiy Zyuganov, leader of the Russian Federation 
Communist 
Party, who once actively participated in the activities of the 
NSF and is now one of the initiators of the creation of the 
Accord for Russia movement, told the ITAR-TASS correspondent 
that he was still advocating the strengthening of the patriotic 
movement and the unification of all national-patriotic forces. 
In his view, this unification is impeded on the one hand, by 
the policy of the authorities and on the other, by increasing 
radicalism among nationalist patriots, both left- and right-wing. 

</TEXT>

