<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Pessimism </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows Pessimism </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004142094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1101 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004142094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] "The agreement on civic peace in Russia will be 
prepared but it will change nothing in the political situation 
in the country." This is the view of 71.5 percent of 
respondents who participated in the opinion poll conducted by 
the independent service Vox Populi headed by Professor Boris 
Grushin, member of the Presidential council, in late March - 
early April. As many as 400 public figures, deputies of the 
State Duma, leaders of executive power bodies, leaders of 
political parties, prominent entrepreneurs, military commanders, 
media representatives, and scientific and cultural workers 
participated in the poll. 
  According to 15 percent of the opinion poll's participants, 
"the agreement will be prepared and will reach its goal," 6.5 
percent said the "the agreement will not be prepared at all." 
Military commanders and media leaders, 88 percent and 80 
percent respectively, are especially pessimistic with respect to 
peace and accord. There were more optimists among the executive 
leaders (34 percent) and directors of state enterprises (18 
percent). 

</TEXT>

