<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Democratic Russia Planning New Political Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Democratic Russia Planning New Political Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004223794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2054 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004223794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Belsky] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 20 TASS--The Moscow branch of the 
Democratic Russia Movement welcomed plans to create a liberal 
conservative party, likely to be called "Russia's Choice", and 
announced readiness to help organize it. 
  A resolution to this effect was passed at the report-back 
election conference of Democratic Russia's Moscow branch. The 
initiative to set up a new party was moved by the Russia's 
Choice parliamentary faction led by key reformer Yegor Gaydar. 
  According to most speakers at the conference, the new party 
is to promote "consolidation of democratic forces". Ilya 
Zaslavskiy, a Democratic Russia leader, said "the powerful, 
disciplined political association of reformers" would 
counterbalance opposition forces presently gathering strength. 
The planned organization based on dual membership "is by no 
means counterpoised to the Democratic Russia Movement", 
Zaslavskiy emphasised. 
  However, some of the Democratic Russia leaders do not share 
this view, for example Lev Ponomaryov, Dmitriy Katayev and Gleb 
Yakunin. According to Yakunin, "creation of the party will bury 
the Moscow branch of Democratic Russia" by turning it into a 
mere appendage to the political organization headed by Gaydar. 

</TEXT>

