<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin `Secretly' Grants Funds to Volskiy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin `Secretly' Grants Funds to Volskiy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2004130194 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 19 Apr 94 
First Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM2004130194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Vladimir Kucherenko report: "Secretly and Retrospectively"] </F>
  [Text] Premier V. Chernomyrdin signed Directive No. 451-R 
31 March. 
  Under this document the Russian Union of Industrialists and 
Entrepreneurs, headed by A. Volskiy, is allocated 1.2 billion 
rubles from the government's reserve fund. And in the first 
quarter of the year, which has already ended! 
  The aim is a fine one -- to ensure that enterprises with 
competitive technologies have enough funds to take part in 
Washington's "Technology From Russia" exhibition, which will run 
from 4 through 15 May. But why is this being done secretly, 
without coordination with the legislators? Why are the 
candidates to take part in the exhibition being selected not by 
the state but by a social organization? It seems a state, 
legally ratified program for support for highly developed 
production facilities ought to be adopted to define the specific 
recipients of budgetary aid. 
  It remains unclear just how controls will ensure that 
taxpayers' funds are spent strictly as they should be. And why 
is aid going without any competition to one out of hundreds of 
industrialists' social organizations, rather than to the 
Federation of Commodity Producers, say? All this runs directly 
counter both to the principles of a healthy market and to the 
idea of strengthening a rule-of-law state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

