<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Group Says Government Wants To Control Media </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Group Says Government Wants To Control Media </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004140794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1257 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Ivanova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 20 TASS -- Efforts to seize full 
control over the mass media are becoming increasingly marked, 
according to Aleksey Simonov, head of the Foundation for 
Protecting Openness. He told a news conference on Wednesday 
that these efforts included the intention of the Russian 
Committee for the Press "to take all publishing facilities into 
one fist", as well as too wider powers to be given to the 
Federal Broadcasting Service under a law which is being drafted 
at the moment. 
  A bill on state support of the "fourth power" by granting it 
tax preferences has stumbled in parliament. For this reason, 
the press will have to live on state subsidies this and next 
year. 
  The situation over broadcasting media is even more strained, 
since they have been continually threatened with strikes of 
communications workers. Simonov expressed puzzle as to why the 
state cannot "free" the TV and radio companies it cannot 
maintain. He also complained about disunity of journalists' 
actions in solving these issues. 
  The Foundation for Protecting Openness, numbering only five 
staffers, was founded three years ago. It is engaged in 
monitoring violations of journalists' rights throughout the 
Commonwealth of independent States. The foundation also set up 
a mass media law school and participated in actions aimed at 
release of newsmen illegally jailed in zones of inter-ethnic 
conflicts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

