<H3> <TI>   `Brain Drain' Increase Causes `Alarm' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Brain Drain' Increase Causes `Alarm' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2004151994 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 20 Apr 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> PM2004151994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "'Brain Drain' Continues"] </F>
  [Text] Around 100,000 people leave Russia every year. 
Russian Federation Labor Minister Gennadiy Melikyan reported 
this to an RIA correspondent. He said that the level of 
emigration has doubled as compared with 1989. From what the 
minister said, thousands of skilled workers, specialists, and 
representatives of creative professions are leaving the country, 
which may have a negative effect on its intellectual and labor 
potential. "The `brain drain' process from fundamental science, 
the defense complex, and sectors which have found themselves in 
the most difficult situation in the period of the restructuring 
of the economy, is generating particularly great alarm." 
  At the same time, the minister noted that the influx of 
refugees into Russia, which has assumed a "steady and constant 
nature," is growing. 

</TEXT>

