<H3> <TI>   Government Approves 1994 Social Policy Guidelines </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Approves 1994 Social Policy Guidelines </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104125094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1214 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 21 TASS -- The Russian Government 
defined as the main goal of its social policy for 1994 
"stabilisation of living standards of Russian people with their 
subsequent improvement as the economy develops". This goal was 
formulated in the social policy guidelines of the Russian 
Government for 1994, a document which was adopted by the 
Presidium of the Russian Government at its meeting on Thursday. 
  The document stresses that "The Russian Government is guided 
by the premise that a fruitful and balanced social policy is a 
necessary condition to continue reforms, to consolidate their 
social basis and to improve the social and political situation 
in the country". 
  The main directions of the social policy for 1994 provide 
for 
creating economic and legal conditions which will stimulate the 
able-bodied part of society to ensure its well-being with highly 
productive labour. They also provide for supporting optimum 
correlation between the incomes of the able-bodied part of 
population and disabled citizens, for ensuring the main social 
guarantees and for preventing mass unemployment. 
  To realise these aims in 1994, the government plans to 
concentrate on preventing a drop in real cash incomes of 
population, ensuring a weighted balance of economic interests 
and material possibilities of hired labour, businessmen and 
disabled citizens as well as reforming the public health and 
public education systems, culture and housing. The government 
will also concentrate on creating new jobs for population and 
stepping up work to retrain labour. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

