<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin: Economic Changes Need Private Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shokhin: Economic Changes Need Private Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004195494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1729 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Yezhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 20 TASS -- "Radical changes in the 
Russian economy will take place only alongside the influx of 
private investments, rather than credits from international 
financial organisations," said Russian Vice-Premier Aleksandr 
Shokhin at a meeting with journalists on Wednesday. The news 
conference was devoted to international economic cooperation and 
investments into Russian economy. 
  According to the vice-premier, the International Monetary 
Fund is practically prepared to grant Russia the second part of 
a three- billion "system credit." At a session of the board of 
IMF managers opening in Washington this week preparations will 
be launched for granting a standard credit worth 4 billion 
dollars, Shokhin said. 
  In his opinion, an annual session of EBRD managers held in 
St. Petersburg last week showed a high level of Russia's 
interaction with Western partners. He pointed out that Russia 
would like to attract more private investments for the 
development of the oil and gas sector. The government is 
prepared to accept such investments on privileged terms, he 
said. For instance, the value added tax, which caused great 
concern of foreign and domestic investors, has been practically 
lifted from foreign investments into Russia, Shokhin said. 
  Until recently, Russian enterprises had to pay a lot of 
money 
to the state for equipment it imported from abroad. Now, as 
soon as the equipment is installed, the whole amount of tax 
levied on the equipment will be returned. As for the imports of 
material and monetary means for the formation of the fixed 
stock, they are exempt from taxes altogether, Shokhin said. 
  The government does not forget potential domestic investors, 
the vice-premier said. At present, the government is working 
out a plan of making a bigger number of attractive enterprises 
available for privatisation after a voucher stage is over than 
their original number offered for privatisation. On the other 
hand, stable inflation rates reached by the government will 
inevitably bring about the reduction of bank interest rates, 
which is a major condition for encouraging investments into 
industry, Shokhin said. 

</TEXT>

