<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Investments in Oil, Gas Industries Sought </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Investments in Oil, Gas Industries Sought </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004214994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1347 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004214994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Before the end of the year, Russia is likely to have 
a law on oil and gas and another three or four legislative acts 
designed to attract foreign investments into the country's oil 
and gas industry, said Deputy Energy Minister Anatoliy Shatalov. 
  He told the Oil and Gas '94 international conference in 
Moscow on Wednesday that, in addition, Russia is shortly due to 
join the European Energy Charter Treaty, which would provide 
more favorable conditions for foreign investors. He said Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin's December decree entitling Russian and 
foreign businesses investing in the exploration and development 
of mineral deposits to part of the minerals extracted from them 
made it possible to embark on major oil and gas projects. 
  One of such projects is Sakhalin 1, Shatalov said. He said 
the Russian Economics and Environmental Protection Ministries 
would soon consider the project and that a contract on it would 
be signed before the end of the year. Another project is soon 
due to be launched, Sakhalin 2, to be handled by the MMMSM 
international consortium, Shatalov said. 
  Output-sharing agreements will also be signed with foreign 
firms which are to work deposits in the Timan-Pechora oil and 
gas province encompassing parts of northwestern Russia's Komi 
Republic and Arkhangelsk Region. 
  Apart from that, Russia's Energy Ministry and the 
administrations of the country's Volgograd and Saratov Regions 
by May 20 are due to finish talks with the French company Elf 
Aquitane on developing oil and gas deposits in the two regions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

