<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   New U.S. Ambassador Presents Credentials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New U.S. Ambassador Presents Credentials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2104035994 Baku Azerbaycan Radio Televiziyasi Television 
Network in Azeri 1600 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2104035994 </F>
<F P=104>  Baku Azerbaycan Radio Televiziyasi Television 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Azeri </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Azerbaijani President Geydar Aliyev today received 
the U.S. ambassador extraordinary and plenipotentiary to our 
Republic, Richard Kozlaric. Our correspondent Sakit Ochakhly 
reports: 
  [Begin Ochakhly recording] New U.S. Ambassador Richard 
Kozlaric presented his credentials to Geydar Aliyev at the 
presidential residence today. The ambassador noted that as the 
official representative of the United States in Azerbaijan he 
will do everything to develop bilateral ties in a healthy spirit 
and broaden ties in the social, political, scientific, and 
cultural fields. 
  Kozlaric also stated that in his new post he will use every 
means to objectively convey the developments in Azerbaijan to 
the international community, primarily to the country he 
represents, and to speedily end the conflict between Azerbaijan 
and Armenia. He also said that the agreement to be signed with 
Azerbaijan's oil company will open a new phase in economic 
cooperation. 
  President Aliyev congratulated Kozlaric on his appointment 
as 
the U.S. ambassador to our Republic and wished him success in 
such a responsible task. The president noted that the 
development of diplomatic relations with a great country like 
the United States would help to establish closer ties between 
the two peoples. 
  Aliyev briefed the new ambassador on the sociopolitical 
situation in Azerbaijan, Armenia's aggressive policy, and the 
results of the meeting of CIS heads of state in Moscow. He 
noted that everyone knows the problems faced by a country 20 
percent of the land of which has been occupied and that has over 
1 million refugees, yet the United States has imposed an embargo 
on humanitarian assistance to Azerbaijan. He hoped that the new 
ambassador would appraise developments and the situation 
realistically and inform his country that Armenia is an 
occupying state. 
  Later a frank talk was held between Aliyev and Kozlaric. 
They exchanged views on issues of mutual interest. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

