<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official on Peacekeepers' Deployment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official on Peacekeepers' Deployment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004173394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1347 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004173394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] "The deployment of any forces in Abkhazia without 
its leadership's consent is ruled out," the chairman of 
Abkhazia's parliament, Vladislav Ardzinba, told Interfax on 
Wednesday. 
  With reference to the possible participation of military 
contingents from CIS countries in the peace-keeping forces in 
Abkhazia he said that "it is possible only in the framework of 
documents signed on April 4." 
  In comments on the talks on Abkhazia's political status 
which 
began in Geneva on Tuesday Ardzinba stressed that "there is no 
alternative to peace negotiations." According to him, when 
taking part in the negotiating process Abkhazia proceeds from 
the agreements signed in Moscow on April 4." "On the contrary, 
the Georgian side seems to have forgotten about it," the 
Abkhazian leader pointed out. 
  As he said, the statement made on Georgian radio on Monday 
by 
the Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze, as to "the possibility 
of resolving the conflict militarily", cannot be understood in 
any other way. According to Ardzinba, this is "a gross 
violation of the documents signed in Moscow." 
  On April 4 in Moscow the two sides signed a statement on 
ways 
to reach a political solution to the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict 
and an agreement on the voluntary return of refugees and 
displaced persons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-17033 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov077_s_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-077 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhazia Defense Minister on Inguri Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Abkhazia Defense Minister on Inguri Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004161094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1101 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004161094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Abkhazia's Defense Minister Sultan Sosnaliyev 
considers it unlikely that hostilities between the Abkhazian and 
Georgian formations will resume along the confrontation line of 
the Inguri river. "We are not moving and our opponents do not 
have enough forces to inflict a strike," Sosnaliyev declared in 
an interview with Interfax. As he said, the situation on the 
Inguri river "is very calm now." 
  Sosnaliyev pointed out that the Abkhazian army does not 
intend to cross Abkhazia's "historic border" and to occupy 
Georgian territory. At the same time he said that "as a result 
of the defeat of the Georgian army we could cross the Inguri 
river and move further on." 
  Sosnaliyev talked about the strong support given by Russia's 
Caucasian republics to Abkhazia. He said that this would not 
allow Moscow to render widescale military assistance to Georgia 
while relations with Abkhazia were not regulated. "Russia 
should bear in mind the Caucasian factor," he underlined. 
  Sosnaliyev reported that as many as 12,000 volunteers from 
the North Caucuses had been fighting on the Abkhaz side. "If it 
is necessary, this number can be increased to 50,000," he said. 
  Speaking about the situation in Abkhazia's Kondor canyon 
where Georgian armed detachments have been blocked, Sosnaliyev 
reported that no hostilities are going on there. The Abkhaz 
side proposed to the Georgian fighters to lay down their arms 
and guaranteed their safety. There was no answer to this 
proposal. 
  Sultan Sosnaliyev, aged 52, is a Kabardinian, a colonel of 
the former Soviet Army. He was commander of a regiment and then 
chief of one of the aviation colleges. 
  In August 1992 when the Georgian army entered Abkhazia, 
Sosnaliyev headed the republic's Military council. In December 
1992 he was chief of the army headquarters and in May 1993 -- 
Abkhazia's Defense Minister. In April 1993 Abkhazian parliament 
awarded him the rank of Mayor General and in December -- of 
Lieutenant General. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

