<DOCNO> FBIS4-17034 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov077_s_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-077 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Ethnic Cleansing' Continues in Sukumi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Ethnic Cleansing' Continues in Sukumi </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004201594 Tbilisi First Program Television Network in 
Georgian 1600 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004201594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi First Program Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Georgian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] According to EVRAZIA news agency, the ethnic 
cleansing of Georgians continues in Sukhumi. 
  Thirty Georgians, mainly old people, were evicted from 
Sukhumi on 15 April. Those people who do not obey the 
separatists' demands to leave their own homes invariably 
disappear. 
  Confrontation between the so-called pure-blooded Abkhazians 
and the Abkhazians of Georgian descent, grows day by day. 
According to the separatists, Georgian Abkhazians must not be 
trusted. In their opinion they [Georgian Abkhazians] are fickle 
and if the situation should change, they will side with the 
Georgians. Therefore, the so-called pure Abkhazians are 
creating specialized armed formations for liquidating Georgian 
Abkhazians. These formations do not spare other nationalities 
either. A clear example of the above-mentioned is the mass 
carnage of the Greek population in the village of Odishi by the 
separatists. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-17035 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov077_s_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-077 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Interior Minister Killed in `Terrorist Act' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Interior Minister Killed in `Terrorist Act' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004121394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1200 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi April 20 TASS -- Georgian Deputy Interior 
Minister Georgi Gulua, 38, who headed Georgian Transport Police, 
fell another victim of terrorist acts this morning. He and his 
two subordinates were riddled with bullets when they were 
driving to his office. Terrorists escaped from the place of 
crime unidentified. 
  This is the eighth terrorist act in Georgia against a 
high-ranking government official over the past few months. Law 
enforcement bodies could not identify executors of 
assassinations even once. 
  Head of the State Security Service Igor Georgadze told 
journalists at a recent news conference that Georgia is living 
through a period of fierce struggle between mafia clans, and 
that terrorist acts are inevitable. 

</TEXT>

