<H3> <TI>   `Modern Technology' Employed at Border </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Modern Technology' Employed at Border </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2004120794 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 19 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2004120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [INTERFAX report: "Estonia Equips Border With Modern </F>
Technology"] 
  [Text] Construction of modern technical control 
facilities, including radar, television cameras, and night 
vision instruments, will begin on the Estonian border this 
summer. 
  This was announced in an interview for the paper PAEVALEHT 
by 
Tarmo Kyuts, general director of the Estonian border protection 
department. According to him, at the moment most border guards 
are equipped only with binoculars and automatic weapons. Kyuts 
announced that the most difficult section of the border is the 
"control line with Russia." One of the most profitable criminal 
occupations there is the trade in "live goods." Border guards 
are offerd $50 each to help ferry one Kurd across the 
Russian-Estonian border. Kyuts noted that the organizers of the 
illegal ferrying of people to the northern countries in Russia 
and their assistants in Estonia are making millions. 

</TEXT>

