<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unemployment Rate Rises to 2.22 Percent </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Unemployment Rate Rises to 2.22 Percent </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2004190994 Tallinn BNS in English 1505 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2004190994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Apr 20, BNS -- Estonia as of April 1 had 
registered 19,521 persons as unemployed. The figure makes up 
2.22 percent of the country's population in the working age 
groups. 
  This is the highest recorded unemployment rate in Estonia 
since last May, when the figure rose to 2.6 percent. 
  The Estonian Labor Market Department in its comments to the 
report says the tendency toward higher jobless rates is due to 
the general restructuring under way in the economy, as well as 
the privatization of state companies. Another factor 
contributing to higher rates in Estonia is the establishment of 
local employment record offices in rural areas, which makes it 
easier for residents in more distant areas to come to register. 
  The highest regional unemployment rate for April 1 was 7.33, 
also up from 6.46 percent of March 1, reported in the 
northeastern town of Narva, where 3,545 had been registered as 
out of job. Next on the list came the southeastern Vorumaa 
region with 6.47 percent, or 1,500 jobless, and its neighboring 
Polva region with 6.31 percent, or 1,171 jobless. Unemployment 
rates were also above five percent in the northeastern 
Ida-Virumaa region with the town of Kohtla- Jarve, as well as on 
the western island of Hiiumaa. 
  The country's capital, Tallinn, still manages to keep 
jobless 
rates low, reporting a meager 0.127-percent unemployment, or 754 
residents officially without a job. 
  Estonia as of March 1 had registered 18,273 jobless, which 
corresponds to a national unemployment rate of 2.08 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-17048 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov077_u_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-077 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saeima Fails To Authorize Agreements Signing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saeima Fails To Authorize Agreements Signing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2104110894 Tallinn BNS in English 1003 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2104110894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Apr 21, BNS -- During its extraordinary 
plenary meeting Wednesday [20 April] night, the Latvian Saeima 
(parliament) did not authorize the Latvian president, Guntis 
Ulmanis, to sign Latvian-Russian initialed interstate agreements 
because the Latvian National Independence Movement and the 
Homeland and Freedom factions left the plenary meeting's hall 
before the voting for the draft resolution had started. 
  After a long debate, when voting for separate items, the 
Saeima accepted the Latvia's Way drafted resolution providing 
for the the president to be authorized to sign the draft 
agreements, initialed March 15, on complete withdrawal of Russia 
army from Latvia, the withdrawal conditions, terms, order and 
army's legal status during the withdrawal; on Skrunda radar 
station's legal status during its temporary functioning on 
Latvia's soil; on Russian militaries' and their family members' 
protection till the complete army withdrawal. 
  The Saeima also supported the draft resolution's 2nd part 
providing for the Cabinet to form an experts' group to revise 
the draft agreement on Russian retired militaries' and their 
family members' social protection. According to the 
international legal norms, this document must promote the 
elimination of the occupation consequences in Latvia. Becuse 
the two above mentioned Saeima factions left the plenary meeting 
before the voting, the final decision could not be accepted 
because of lack of quorum. 
  After the plenary meeting, President Guntis Ulmanis refused 
to comment the situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

