<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leftist Party Not To Run in Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leftist Party Not To Run in Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2004113394 Tallinn BNS in English 1849 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2004113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Apr 19, BNS -- The leftist Democratic 
Initiative Center [DIC] party will not participate in the local 
government elections in order "not to take away votes from other 
political organizations," said party spokesman Olegs Vovks. 
  The local government election law does not correspond to the 
party's program that supports the franchise of all residents, 
Vovks said. 
  Commeting on the League of Stateless Persons, Vovk said it 
had no rights to represent all 700,000 non-citizens of Latvia in 
the local elections as it wanted to do. 
  The Democratic Initiative Center would endorse a popular 
referendum on citizenship proposing a five year residence 
qualification, language skills and knowledge of basic principles 
of Constitution as terms for naturalization, Vovks said. 
  Vovks conceded that he did not believe that Latvian citizens 
would support DIC version for the country's citizenship law. 
But he said the party would still demand a referendum to bring 
the citizenship problem in the focus of popular attention. 
  DIC was founded in 1989. It has a membership of 53 now. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

