<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lozovoy on Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lozovoy on Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004215294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1347 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004215294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The third round of talks between the presidents of 
North Ossetia and Ingushetia Akhsarbek Galazov and Ruslan Aushev 
will be decisive, head of the temporary administration in the 
state of emergency zone Vladimir Lozovoy said in an interview 
with Interfax in Nazran. 
  The leaders of the two neighboring republics are expected to 
meet in the capital of Kabardino-Balkaria, Nalchik, next week. 
At the previous round of talks the two sides agreed only on the 
preamble to the treaty on the implementation of the Russian 
president's decree on the return of refugees and forced migrants 
in the zone of the Ossetian-Ingush conflict. 
  "If this time talks bring no concrete results, there is no 
sense in wasting time further," Lozovoy believes. In his 
opinion, the Russian Security Council and the Federal Assembly 
will then have "to clearly indicate what the temporary 
administration and the presidents of both republics should do." 
Lozovoy noted that he had established normal working contacts 
with Galazov and Aushev. But in resolving problems he adheres 
only to the policy of the center. "Precisely from this position 
I would like to state that all of us should work for the sake of 
accord in Russia," Lozovoy said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

