<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechens Concerned on Moscow Contacts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechens Concerned on Moscow Contacts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004171794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1347 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At a meeting in the office of the Chechen President 
Dhozkhar Dudayev on Tuesday a letter sent by Russian 
Vice-Premier Sergey Shakhray was discussed. It was allegedly 
submitted to the State Duma marked "Confidential". The 12-page 
document contains recommendations to the Russian leadership 
regarding the tactics and strategy in the resolution of the 
Chechen problem. 
  The Chechen presidential office told Interfax that Shakhray 
recommended that in the settlement of the Russian-Chechen 
relations, the main stakes should be made on political forces 
opposing Dudayev. 
  "This is another sign that Russian diplomacy is not in 
control of the situation," a high-ranking official of the 
Chechen presidential staff pointed out. In his opinion, the 
Russian leadership is currently trying to reanimate supporters 
of the former first secretary of the Chechen-Ingush Regional 
Committee Doka Zavgayev who was dismissed from this post in 1991 
and is now living in Moscow. 
  At a conference in Groznyy the Security Department submitted 
a document to the Chechen president, saying that Shakhray 
maintains close relations with the Chechen opposition. 

</TEXT>

