<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechen Leader Criticizes Dudayev </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechen Leader Criticizes Dudayev </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004225294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1631 
GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004225294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents] </F>
  [Text] Groznyy, 20 Apr -- Any talks or consultations with 
Russia should only be held by persons who have the authorization 
of the people to do so, Yaragi Mamodayev, head of the Government 
of National Trust of Chechnya, believes. In a telephone 
conversation with an ITAR-TASS correspondent today, he said that 
"it is necessary to hold a congress of the Chechen people in the 
near future to work out the basic criteria for solving the 
problem of Russian-Chechen inter-relations." 
  In the words of Yaragi Mamodayev, the government he leads 
has 
already begun preparing this forum. Consultations with the 
chairman of Chechnya's Constitutional Court, well-known public 
and religious figures, and representatives of various political 
bodies have been held. I would like it to be understood in 
Moscow, Yaragi Mamodayev said, that Dhozkhar Dudayev's 
unjustified postponement of the beginning of the Russian-Chechen 
talks does not reflect the position of the whole of Chechen 
society. A people's congress needs to be held to work out this 
position. 
  Yaragi Mamodayev again pointed out that open appeals by the 
Russian side to forces opposing Dhozkhar Dudayev risked 
aggravating the political split in Chechnya and could become an 
obstacle in the negotiating process. Yaragi Mamodayev distances 
himself from the opposition, explaining that he was appointed 
head of government by the legal Chechen Parliament in April of 
last year and therefore, represents the legitimate executive 
power in the republic. 
  Yaragi Mamodayev believes that the Russian leadership should 
have determined at the outset which authorities in Chechnya it 
considered legal and only then should it have begun any talks or 
consultations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

