<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tatar Vice Premier on Economic Independence </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tatar Vice Premier on Economic Independence </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004215794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1819 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004215794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The sole right to independently maintain foreign 
economic relations envisioned in the power-sharing treaty with 
the Russian Federation is insufficient to attract foreign 
investments, Tatar Vice Prime Minister Ravil Muratov said in 
Kazan Wednesday. He added that Tatarstan needed to win over the 
right to independently set export and import duties taking into 
account its own strategic interests and the right to set export 
quotas for oil for no less than five years. At present, the 
quotas are set for one year only. Otherwise, the Tatar 
government will be unable to guarantee foreign investors return 
on their capital. 
  Besides its external problems, Tatarstan needs to solve 
internal ones such as the introduction of private ownership of 
land in accordance with the Constitution, heal the credit and 
financial systems, create market institutions -- private 
enterprises, leasing agencies, insurance companies, banks -- 
capable of maintaining direct contacts with foreign partners. 
  Muratov said the present state of Tatarstan's economy was 
critical and needed immediate drastic reforms. 

</TEXT>

