<H3> <TI>   Problems With Tyumen Oil Output Production </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Problems With Tyumen Oil Output Production </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2004104994 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 19 Apr 94 
First Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM2004104994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Oil Dead End"] </F>
  [Text] Tyumen oil workers are not only losing the rhythm 
of oil extraction but also the market for their product. Uray 
oil workers, for instance, have been forced to cut their oil 
extraction by 200 tonnes a day. 
  And it is not only the Uray workers, Aleksandr Filippenko, 
head of the Khanti-Mansiysk Autonomous Okrug Administration, 
confirmed. All oil production in the Ob River area is currently 
in a similar situation. Why? The first reason is obvious -- it 
is simply unprofitable to extract the oil. On average in the Ob 
region the prime cost of a single tonne of oil is 100,000 rubles 
[R], yet it is sold (that is, simply pumped into the pipeline) 
for R65,000. But the oilmen cannot even get this money, because 
potential purchasers have no money either, and they are tired of 
selling on credit. It is, as they say, a vicious circle. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

