<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Agree on International Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Agree on International Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104100694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0929 
GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2104100694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 21 Apr -- A meeting between Boris Yeltsin, 
Bill Clinton, representatives of the United Nations and the 
European Union, to settle the Balkan conflict is possible within 
a month, Vyacheslav Kostikov, Russian Federation president's 
press secretary, told a Kremlin briefing today. 
  He said that late last night Boris Yeltsin and Bill Clinton 
had a long telephone conversation, lasting some 40 minutes. 
Vyacheslav Kostikov noted that during the conversation the 
Russian Federation president said "Russia and the United States 
have a common path of democracy and partnership, there is no 
crack in the partnership, but a sober and pragmatic account of 
national interests does exist." 
  The Russian Federation president again confirmed Russia's 
position with regard to NATO's bombing raids. "Russia is not a 
supporter of any party to the conflict, but it does have and 
will continue to have its own levers to influence the situation 
in the region," Kostikov said. He also said that during his 
telephone conversation with Bill Clinton, Boris Yeltsin yet 
again came out "categorically against bombing raids not 
previously agreed upon with Russia, and in response, got 
Clinton's assurance that the USA would refrain from sharp 
actions in this direction." 
  Vyacheslav Kostikov thinks that in order to settle the 
Balkan 
crisis, it is necessary to find "a single plan and to set about 
implementing it." "The attempt by the parties involved to get 
individual dividends from the crisis is doomed to fail and is 
not constructive," the press secretary emphasized. 

</TEXT>

