<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Decisions To Be Made `Jointly' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Decisions To Be Made `Jointly' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2104100194 Paris AFP in English 0942 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2104100194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Moscow, April 21 (AFP) -- Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin and his US counterpart Bill Clinton have agreed to 
hold an international summit meeting on the Bosnia crisis, 
possibly as soon as next month, a spokesman said Thrusday. 
  Yeltsin's spokesman, Vyacheslav Kostikov, told reporters at 
a 
briefing that summit was discussed in a phone conversation 
between the two leaders late Wednesday and would include in 
addition to themselves leaders from the United Nations, the 
European Union and the warring sides in the former Yugoslavia. 
  The two leaders, who spoke for about 40 minutes, agreed that 
the conference required careful planning but stressed that the 
situation was "red-hot" in Bosnia, Kostikov said. 
  "The assurance was given that all decisions to resolve the 
conflict would be jointly taken", Kostikov added. 
  "Any attempt at an individual, unilateral solution is not 
constructive," he said. 
  Yeltsin reiterated his firm stand in favor of peaceful 
solutions and his rejection of "any type of bombing" by NATO 
warplanes in Bosnia. [passage omitted] 
  In Paris, French President Francois Mitterrand expressed 
satisfaction over the planned conference, which he said should 
be held as soon as possible considering the urgency of the 
situation, his spokesman Jean Musitelli said Thursday. 

</TEXT>

