<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Urges Parties To Coordinate Bosnia Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Urges Parties To Coordinate Bosnia Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104133994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1327 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev has called 
for Russia, the UN, the European Union, and other parties acting 
to resolve the crisis in Yugoslavia to coordinate a single stand 
on Bosnia. He expressed this position in Moscow on Wednesday at 
the end of his meeting with the Co-Chairmen of the Geneva Peace 
Conference on Former Yugoslavia Lord Owen and Thorvald 
Stoltenberg. As Kozyrev said, "among the Bosnian Serbs there is 
a party of war, waiting for fresh air strikes to continue the 
war. It's people from this party who have been shelling 
hospitals and other civilian targets in Gorazde." 
  However, in the interests of all the Serbs the war must be 
stopped on fair terms and the lifting of sanctions should be 
gradually pressed for, Kozyrev said. These interests of the 
Serbs and of the other conflicting sides should be given a real 
chance, he stressed. In his words, at Wednesday's session of 
Russia's Security Council the Bosnian problem was discussed in 
the same key and on the basis of the statement made by President 
Yeltsin on Tuesday. We will do whatever we can to stop the 
bloodshed in Gorazde, introduce disengagement troops and put an 
end to the confrontation there. Kozyrev disclosed that in a 
telephone conversation with the American Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher he had asked him to send to Moscow the US 
President's Special Envoy on Former Yugoslavia Charles Redman, 
whose expertise, as Kozyrev put it, is as essential as that of 
Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg. 
  Regrettably, Christopher declined to give a clear-cut 
answer. 
So, the door remains open, Kozyrev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-17091 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov077_a_94015" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-077 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Common' Position on Bosnia Sought </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Common' Position on Bosnia Sought </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104140994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1339 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow, April 21 (TASS) -- "It is time to decide 
what result the international community wants to see in Yugoslav 
settlement," Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mikhail Demurin 
said. 
  Russia favours a "common and single position of the world 
community" on this problem, Demurin said. He believes such 
position should include "clear benchmarks and determination for 
ensuring the implementation of the adopted decisions," as well 
as "reflect the will of the international community to meet the 
rightful interests of all sides involved in the settlement which 
are moving along the path of peace." 
  He stressed that "there should be no doubts about the 
ultimate goal." in his view, it is important for Russia, the 
United States, the European Union, the United Nations and all 
other concerned countries to have a "common and clear-cut 
position." "Seeing the prospects for political settlement and 
having a clear vision of what the post-war future of the 
countries that emerged on the territory of the former Yugoslavia 
should be, one can make decisions on intermediate steps," 
Demurin said. 
  He warned, however, that such steps, if taken without clear 
understanding of the consequences, may be harmful for the 
settlement process in the former Yugoslavia. 
  Demurin described as "allegations" statements by today's 
newspaper IZVESTIYA that the Russian Foreign Ministry's position 
on the Bosnian crisis has allegedly not been supported by 
President Boris Yeltsin and is now being reworked. 
  He stressed that "these allegations are far from the foreign 
policy and the essence of Russia's foreign policy initiatives." 
He noted that there are "no disagreements, let alone 
contradictions" between the president and the Foreign Ministry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

