<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Seen as Victim of `Inner Apparatus Intrigue' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Seen as Victim of `Inner Apparatus Intrigue' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2104101094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 21 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK2104101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Vladimir Abarinov report in the "Power" column: "The </F>
Bosnian Crisis as a Cause for Apparatus Intrigue. The Security 
Council Has Resolved To Continue Negotiations With the Serbs"] 
  [Text] The subject of a Bosnian settlement has suddenly 
taken on a scandalous turn. As SEGODNYA reported earlier, the 
day before yesterday the Russian Foreign Affairs Ministry 
prepared the text of a presidential statement, but the final 
text that emerged from the Kremlin office that day was a 
strongly watered-down version. It is not ruled out that this is 
a totally different text. At the same time, a Foreign Ministry 
spokesman denied "reports by some mass media outlets" about 
differences between Andrey Kozyrev and Vitaliy Churkin on the 
Bosnian problem. This statement is more than suspicious: At 
least we are not aware of any such reports. Yesterday morning a 
new denial followed, this time by Air Force Commander Yevgeniy 
Podkolzin. The general described as "speculation" reports that 
the Russian battalion can be withdrawn from Sarajevo. During 
the whole day there was a solid flow of denials and similar 
statements via various communications channels. Toward evening 
the presidential press service circulated a report about a 
session of the Russian Federation Security Council. The text 
says that the session, "in addition to the planned agenda," 
considered the "situation in Bosnia and the tragedy in Gorazde." 
It resolved: There is no tragedy. This is our comment on the 
phrase: "The possibility of a peace agreement on settling the 
conflict remains real." 
  Judging by a number of signs, what is now happening Moscow 
is 
not just an attempt to prevent a large-scale use of force in 
Bosnia, but an inner apparatus intrigue whose victim could 
become the president's special envoy, Vitaliy Churkin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

