<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Deputy Speaker Calls for Russian-Serb Union </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Deputy Speaker Calls for Russian-Serb Union </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004214694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1347 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004214694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aleksandr Vengerovskiy, deputy chairman of the State 
Duma, the lower house of the Russian parliament, has called for 
a military and political union of Russia and Serbia and for 
Russia to play a more active role in the former Yugoslavia. 
  "It is not NATO or the United Nations that should dictate 
their terms to the Serbs but Russia that must determine the 
policy there," said Vengerovskiy, who is one of the leaders of 
extreme nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovskiy's Liberal Democratic 
Party. 
  At a news conference in Moscow on Wednesday, Vengerovskiy 
criticized the Duma's decision to suspend debates on the 
situation in ex-Yugoslavia until the return of a Duma delegation 
due to leave for the war-torn country on Thursday. The Duma is 
trying "to get off easy by setting up another commission, which 
would engage in political tourism. 
  Commenting on his recent trip to Pyongyang, Vengerovskiy 
said 
relations between Russia and North Korea are today at a "zero" 
level. Asked whether he discussed the issue of the North 
Korea's nuclear facilities during his visit, he said that, when 
he asked whether Pyongyang had an atom bomb, his hosts replied, 
"We don't know." 

</TEXT>

