<H3> <TI>   Grachev Meets With Turkish Counterpart in Moscow </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev Meets With Turkish Counterpart in Moscow </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004194994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1723 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004194994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Andrey Palaria and Sergey </F>
Ostanin] 
  [Text] Moscow April 20 TASS -- The four-day official visit 
to Russia by Turkish Defence Minister Mehmet Golhan is expected 
to give a boost to Russian-Turkish military ties. 
  The first tangible results of the visit that begun just 
today 
was the signing an agreement on military and technical 
cooperation between the two countries by Russian Defence 
Minister Pavel Grachev and Golhan in Moscow on Wednesday. 
  During the talks, the two ministers discussed Russia's 
peace-keeping activity in the United Nations and the CIS. They 
also focused on the restriction of Russia's positions in the 
south, following the disintegration of the Soviet Union and the 
emergence of the Commonwealth of Independent States. 
  The sides also touched upon the Karabakh conflict, the 
Bosnian crisis and the implementation of the CIS collective 
security agreement. 
  Grachev will have a one-to-one meeting with his Turkish 
counterpart on Sunday to discuss prospects for military and 
technical cooperation between Russia and Turkey and other issues 
of mutual concern. 
  On Thursday, Golhan will lay a wreath at the tomb of the 
unknown soldier in Moscow, visit the Mil design bureau and tour 
a motorised infantry brigade. 

</TEXT>

