<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev, Golhan View Defense Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev, Golhan View Defense Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2004183294 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1648 
GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2004183294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] A military, technical, and defense industry 
cooperation agreement was signed between Turkey and Russia in 
Moscow today. The agreement was signed by Russian Defense 
Minister Pavel Grachev and National Defense Minister Mehmet 
Golhan. Both ministers noted that the agreement, which was 
signed at the end of talks between the two countries' 
delegations, bases bilateral relations on a sound foundation. 
During the talks, Russia once again expressed the changes it 
wants to introduce with regard to the implementation of the CFE 
agreement and briefed Golhan on NATO's Partnership for Peace 
plan and the sharing of the Black Sea fleet with Ukraine. 
  After the signing ceremony, the two ministers replied to 
questions by reporters. Grachev declared that Russia received 
approval from Armenia, Georgia, and Azerbaijan concerning the 
bases it wants to establish in the Caucasus, but the 
installation in Azerbaijan will be an early-warning station, 
rather than a base. Pointing out that his country wants to 
deploy Russian troops in bases in the CIS countries with the 
approval of the relevant governments, Grachev added that this 
must also be ratified by the legislative organs of these 
countries. 
  Golhan, in response to a question on Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
declared that from the beginning Turkey has been exerting 
efforts to put an end to the clashes, stressing that the status 
of the Turkish troops to be sent to Bosnia should be approached 
within the framework of these peaceful efforts. 

</TEXT>

