<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur on Upcoming Dniester Leaders Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Snegur on Upcoming Dniester Leaders Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004105394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1008 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Fyodor Angeli] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev [Chisinau] 20 April, TASS -- "A new meeting 
of the Moldovan leadership with leaders of the breakaway 
Dniester Republic is expected to be held shortly. It will be 
attended by representatives from the CSCE and by the Russian 
president's special envoy," Moldovan President Mircea Snegur 
told the newspaper ZEMLYA I LYUDI. 
  "But already before that meeting," he stressed, "all the 
barriers, obstructing economic relations between the left-hand 
and right-hand banks of the Dniester will be eliminated." 
  According to Snegur, customs barriers and other control 
services of the two sides will be abolished and traffic will be 
reopened across the presently blocked bridges." 
  The president again stressed that the Moldovan parliament 
would soon discuss the question of granting a special legal 
status to towns and villages with a compact Gagauz population. 
"After all," he noted, "nobody is encroaching upon the integrity 
of the state. They merely want autonomy within Moldova. Gagauz 
representatives had themselves stated that they could not 
imagine their existence outside the Republic. The point is to 
decentralise the government, to transfer some of its functions 
to the local administration, and to give broader opportunities 
for developing the market relations." 
  The Moldovan leader noted that "if the Republic shuts up in 
its purely national shell, it will not get any support from the 
civilised world. Moldova's prestige on the international arena 
will depend on how it observes human rights, on the state of 
inter-ethnic relations within the country." 

</TEXT>

