<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baltin on `Normal Functioning' of Fleet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Baltin on `Normal Functioning' of Fleet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004155794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1101 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004155794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Extreme political decisions are taken when 
politicians find themselves in a hopeless economic situation, 
Commander of the Black Sea Fleet Admiral Baltin told INTERFAX 
commenting on last week's talks on the Black Sea Fleet. 
  On 15 April, the Russian and Ukrainian presidents came to 
terms on a gradual settlement of the Black Sea Fleet problem on 
the basis of the fleet's division. Ukraine is to have 15 to 20 
percent of the fleet. 
  Baltin believes that Ukraine will fail to ensure the combat 
efficiency of the ships and the normal functioning of the fleet. 
He noted that Ukraine had unilaterally established control over 
35 percent of the Black Sea Fleet. So 65, not 100 percent of 
the fleet will have to be equally divided, he said. 
  Baltin also announced that 18 months ago, Ukraine received a 
missile cruiser, small antisubmarine boats, small amphibious 
ships and a coast-guard boat, all of them new and 65-85 percent 
combat ready. None of these ships have been brought to complete 
combat readiness, said Baltin. 
  He pointed out, meanwhile, that if Ukraine had enough money 
it would have a unique missile cruiser not to be found either in 
the Black Sea, or in the Mediterranean or in the U.S. 6th Fleet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

